subSubSection.paragraph:
Head (
Fig. 5A
) covered with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, and sparse setiferous punctures; setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 6C
); frontoclypeal suture bisinuate, middle portion wide, about half width of clypeus; labrum and clypeus convex and furnished with setae; length of clypeus longer than that of labrum; apex of clypeus weakly lined. Canthus large, acutely triangular but apex rounded, furnished with a few setae. Apex of mandible bifurcate and furnished with two teeth apically on inner margin; lateral angles furnished with setae (
Fig. 4D
). Antennal insertion marginate. Antenna long; segments short, except for first, third and fourth which are long and slender, eleventh segment pointed; all segments setous, fifth through eleventh segments with shorter, denser setae (
Fig. 4C
).

Pronotum (
Fig. 4A
, 
5B
) with blunt lateral tubercles, strongly tapered towards base; groove of anterior margin distinctly impressed a narrow distance from margin, but absent on median portion; posterior marginal groove undulate and complete; lateral basal angles weakly swollen, with two to five long setae near base; surface regularly convex, with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, densely covered with coarse setiferous punctures (
Fig. 6B
); distance between punctures in central portion 1–1.5 times their own diameter, denser laterally. Setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 6B
).

Elytra short, leaving apex of pygidium exposed, moderately vaulted in lateral view; lateral sides ovate, widening approaching posterior margin; dorsal surface with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture (
Fig. 6D
), irregularly covered with dense setiferous punctures which are as coarse as on pronotum and separated by 1–3 times their diameter; setae produced just anterior to punctures (
Fig. 6D
); sutural and lateral grooves complete from elytral base to apex; basal areas of elytra weakly convex on either side of suture; humerus strongly protruding anteriorly; epipleu- ron narrow. Scutellum trapezoidal, with setae.

Disc of mesoventrite sparsely furnished with setae and no punctation; process densely furnished with setiferous punctures (
Fig. 5C
). Mesepisternum furnished with a few setiferous punctures (
Fig.5C
). Surface of metaventrite with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture (
Fig. 6A
), and central area covered with setiferous punctures, lateral area more densely covered with setiferous punctures; setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 6A
). Surface of sternites with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, sparsely covered with setiferous punctures. In male, posterior margin of 7th sternite evenly curved (
Fig. 5D
). In female, posterior margin of 7th sternite straight, but bisinuate on central portion (
Fig. 5E
).

Male genitalia as shown in 
Fig. 7
A–F: 8th sternite furnished with setae, cylindrical, membrane long, allowing for posterior horizontal extension (
Fig. 7E, F
); spiculum fan-shaped (
Fig. 7D
); median struts of median lobe ap- proximately 2.5 times as long as median lobe (
Fig. 7A
); apex of median lobe pointed and inclined to one side (
Fig. 7B
); paramere not developed (
Fig. 7C
).

